SLIDE 3 — The Real Question
What Does Delivery Currently Depend On?
People remembering dependencies
Informal escalation paths
Senior individuals absorbing chaos
Context living in heads and inboxes
Plans explained repeatedly, not derived
Key message
Delivery depends on people synchronizing manually — every day.
Diagram prompt
“Network diagram of people nodes connected by many dotted lines (calls, chats, meetings).
Dependencies are implicit, floating between people rather than systems.”
SLIDE 4 — Manual Traction Works… But at a Cost
The Hidden Cost of Manual Traction
Cognitive overload on senior roles
Risk concentrated in a few individuals
Replanning happens mentally, not visibly
Onboarding new teams is slow
Leadership decisions rely on summaries, not signals
Key message
Manual traction creates drag, not failure.
Diagram prompt
“Same delivery network as before, now with subtle friction icons (weights, resistance arrows).
Delivery still moves forward, but slowly and unevenly.”
SLIDE 5 — The Leverage Gap
Success Today Is Achieved Despite the System
The SDLC does not capture:
